Another study, the European one, concluded that there was a difference in mortality between patients who had been screened and those who did not.
This study also demonstrated, with follow-up after 12 years, that there is a 30-40% greater chance of metastases if not detected.
I therefore recommend the test from 50 years of age, or from 40 years of age if you have a direct parent who has already had prostate cancer.
