The key is to make the right decision once we've detected cancer.
There are aggressive cancers and others that are indolent.
We really need to make the patient understand the degree of risk of his cancer, by offering him the options, not necessarily treating prostate cancers that do not affect long-term life, and instead opting, in these cases, for active surveillance of the disease.
Today, many men in whom cancer is detected will not be treated, because their cancer is not aggressive and does not threaten their lives.
We'll suggest they do active surveillance, and if the disease progresses, we'll give them treatment.
