The Higgs boson in husked
The announcement of the probable discovery of the Higgs boson created a whole stir last summer, and for cause.
It is believed that this boson participates in the mechanism responsible for the mass of all things in the Universe, just like that.
And then, this is the last particle whose existence is predicted by the Standard Model - our best, or "less worse" explanation of the nature and behavior of the matter - but which has not yet been empirically observed.
But for physicists, it is not yet entirely certain that it is the Higgs.
We know without a shadow of a doubt that we hold an authentic new particle, and that it looks much like the Higgs boson predicted by the Standard Model.
In addition, new data unveiled this week at a major physics conference in Kyoto seem to confirm this, but there is still a lack of data to be absolutely certain.
Let us suppose, however, that this is the Higgs, since the chances of being wrong seem thin, and let us see what this is all about.
There is a fatally unavoidable law in this low world that two things cannot be found in the same place at the same time.
No way to break that rule - and don't try too hard, you'll hurt yourself.
Although particle physics is a very strange world, it turns out that it also has such a law: Pauli's principle of exclusion, which states that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state" - this "state" consisting roughly in some of their characteristics.
From there, physicists classify the particles into two categories.
In one corner, there are good citizens called fermions, who wisely obey Pauli's principle.
And in the other, the bosons, a dirty bunch of anarchists who have no respect for anything - in any case, not for this principle, which means that they can really be in the same place at the same time.
These bosons are then divided into two groups, according to the site (absolutely extraordinary, moreover) The Particle Adventure, of the Berkeley Laboratories: the mesons, which we will not approach here, and the "particles of force", through which the great forces of nature spread and to which the Higgs boson would somehow be related.
These bosons, it must be emphasized here, are not all beasts as exotic as one might think.
In fact, if you can read this chronicle, it is thanks to a boson of extraordinary banality: the photon, or the "particle of light" that is the "messenger" of electromagnetic force.
When, in fact, a particle with an electrical charge accelerates or changes direction, it "distangs" the electromagnetic field in this precise place, a bit like a rock thrown into a pond.
From this "disadvantage" arises an electromagnetic wave (from light, or infrared, or ultraviolet, etc.), and this wave is nothing but a photon - and therefore, one of the bosons "bearers of force".
More stable field
The same applies to the Higgs boson, except that it is another field, the Higgs field, which must be "disturbed" for this boson to appear.
However, this Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; to excite it, it is necessary to reach very, very high energies, somewhat as if it were a frozen pond whose only a very large rock could ride the surface.
That's why it takes a huge particle accelerator like the CERN - the Large Hadron Collider is a 27 km ring of circumference! - to reach such energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again useful to explain the relationship between the Higgs and the mass.
It is not all the particles, nor all the materials, that interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do, but others don't - a piece of paper, for example, will never keep itself on a fridge.
And in the same way, it is not all particles that interact with the Higgs field: those that do have a mass, while the others (like the photon, here) do not have one.
Now, what is it that "can bring" all this research, asks Mrs Plamondon?
For science, this is used to verify the validity of the Standard Model (MS), and it also allows physicists to scrutinize any discrepancy between the observations and predictions of the MS.
Indeed, there are many who wish very much that they could be found, because the slightest difference could open a door on a "physical new" and shut some holes in the Model.
This one, it must be said, still has enormous deficiencies, not proposing any explanation for gravity (ops!) or dark matter, which forms about 80% of the matter of the Universe (re-ops!).
But we haven't found any such deviations at CERN so far.
Impacts
The impact of this research on Mr. and Mrs. All-World's daily lives is more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there will be no such research.
Here: In the early 1960s, laser pioneers in Bell Laboratories did not suspect the revolution that their work was going to trigger.
They were seeing scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, we have already heard fire from physicist Willard Boyle - who worked in the Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who himself developed the first continuous laser (the first were pulsed), in 1962 -, initially the laser was rather seen as a "laboratory gadget".
Imagine...
And then, applications can also come from all the instrumentation that surrounds the research.
For example, this same Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor in 1969, during his optical work.
This sensor, although not at all its original intent, now serves as an "eye" for all digital cameras in the world, and earned it the 2009 Nobel Prize in Physics.
This of course does not mean that LHC activities will necessarily transform our lives, but it means that, really, we never know...
Palliative care - The best way to die...
With its Commission dying in dignity, Quebec recently debated the delicate issue of the end of life.
The debate must resume shortly as a bill is being prepared.
However, much remains to be done in this essential area.
The Devoir tried to look at it more closely.
Just a few weeks ago, Mr. L. was still living alone in his apartment in Montérégie.
The prostate cancer that was gnawing at him had left him with a two-year rest.
"They had given me five years to live, I was seven years old," he said, half-fig half-raisin, lying in his bed at the palliative care house Victor-Gadbois, in Beloeil, where he arrived the day before.
"But it's always a shock, you can't be prepared for that," he says.
The disease does its work: a huge weakness that prevents it from going to the toilet alone, and even eating alone.
Attached to an appetizing lunch, he agrees to let himself be helped to eat, resigned.
Courageous, he even smiles, talks to strangers who deal with him, brings him his medicine, offers him a bath.
The courage of ordinary death.
"My biggest wish is to be cured of diarrhea, it's humiliating," he says.
A few hours later, the team found a cure for this disease.
" In our life, we learn that a man pisses on his feet, " says Pierre Brodeur, a psychologist at Victor-Gadbois' house.
Returning to the stage of the child, for some people, is an unacceptable humiliation.
"It depends on the person's ability to accept the regression," he notes.
For, in the opinion of several people working in palliative care, great moments are taking place at the very heart of this regression.
Patients entering the palliative care home Victor-Gadbois all suffer from cancer.
They have a maximum life expectancy of three months.
At this point, the "team of doctors and nurses around them no longer provides so-called "curative" care.
For Ms. A., 89, the worst fear is to die "conscious and stifled".
But the disease made me discover my children.
"I have good children," she adds.
"I have no more wishes in life," she says, before accepting a mask to help her breathe.
In the next few days, however, she is still waiting for a final visit from her son from Italy.
At Victor-Gadbois, with a group of volunteers, care and food aid are provided.
It's palliative care that you give when there's nothing else to do.
To make death more comfortable.
In Quebec, there is a palliative care bed for 11,700 people.
It's very little when we know that we all end up dying one day.
Here, life continues in the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors of the house.
Whether at the level of physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
When dying, we will agree to give mouth care to brandy or Pepsi, as requested.
Diabetes will no longer be required to control their sugar levels.
And death is part of the daily life.
Last night, we had a beer for Mr. X, who died during the night.
This morning, his son will finish the beer at the feet of the deceased.
" We help loved ones as well as patients, " says Nathalie Savard, Director of Care.
At the Victor-Gadbois house, the days follow but do not resemble each other.
Along with an old 93-year-old man who enjoys his last family gathering in the courtyard, well tucked into his pillows while drinking in his honor, a 36-year-old man dies tragically, surrounded by his parents, his wife and two young children, after having tried hard to survive.
" For the past six months, there have always been three to five beds occupied by cancer patients under the age of 45, " worries Dr. Christiane Martel.
53% of the patients admitted to the Victor-Gadbois home arrive from their home, 47% come from the hospital.
Problem of access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care, i.e., care designed to alleviate suffering when a patient has reached the end of his or her life, whether at home, hospital or nursing home.
And several organizations, such as the Victor-Gadbois House and the Society for Home Palliative Care in Greater Montreal, specialize more or less exclusively in cancer care.
It is precisely this great deficiency in Quebec's health care that causes several physicians specialized in palliative care to fear the adoption of a law regulating euthanasia and assisted suicide.
Since October, a manifesto, signed by palliative care leaders including Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe, has been circulating to testify to their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, the Quebec health system is not effective enough to ensure that everyone will be entitled to quality palliative care before euthanasia is accepted.
Recently, she said, I saw a patient spend 14 days in an emergency, in great pain, without doing what was necessary to relieve her.
I'm afraid patients only want to die because they don't get the right care.
And at the same time, several oncologists cling to their patients until the last day, despite the worst predictions.
The survival expectations of Helen Richard were already minimal when she gave up trying chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was stopping the treatment, she told me that she regretted that I stopped fighting, she told me.
Yet she told me I was finished!
No all-powerful care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of the patients who ask to die thank the caregivers for not having acceded to their request after they were relieved of their pain by a palliative care team.
But it must be said that palliative care is not absolutely all-powerful in the treatment of pain.
According to Elsie Monereau, Director of Palliative Care at the Society of Palliative Home Care in Greater Montreal, patients would be refractory to pain treatment in 8% of cases.
At the very end of life, doctors often resort to palliative sedation, which means sleeping the patient until the time of death, either sporadically or permanently.
We can no longer pretend not to hear that part of the suffering.
Increasingly, the unrelieved patient will have the opportunity to have this palliative sedation.
Sick people who are not relieved always say the same sentence: "I want to die. "
But that doesn't necessarily mean "I want you to euthanize me," it means "I want to be relieved."
