With Bitcoin, pay and sell without banks
The opposite is true of current currency exchanges based on central banks, identified transactions and processing costs between stakeholders.
Moreover, as often in these technologies, a political vision is palpable: the conviction that the current monetary system, made of banking monopolies, leads to financial crises.
In fact, Bitcoin, invented by Satoshi Nakamoto (a pseudonym), is both a virtual currency (but convertible into dollars, euros...) and a secure exchange protocol like BitTorrent, which allows for the exchange of pair-to-pair files.
About 200,000 transactions have already been recorded through 15,000 computers on the network.
A small thousand websites accept bitcoins as gifts or as a means of payment.
The bitcoin price, after reaching a top of 30 dollars (23 euros) in June 2011, fell to 2 dollars, five months later, before returning today around ten dollars (the courses are listed on the bitcoincharts.com website).
Nothing very impressive, compared to world trade in real currency or in financial products.
However, the European Central Bank (ECB) took an interest in this in a report on virtual currencies published in October.
It describes bitcoin as "the most successful virtual currency", "in competition with the dollar or the euro" and "similar to conventional currencies".
Bitcoin stands out from other types of virtual currency such as "credits", used to advance in a video game that you win by playing or that you can buy (and sometimes exchange in return).
The Facebook social network has also developed this kind of system.
But each time, a central authority controls and deals with trade.
With Bitcoin, all network nodes are both account book depositors, auditors, money issuers, and buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Each transaction between two users is actually made between two e-mail addresses in the way of an e-mail.
Except that a user can choose a different address for each payment, thus ensuring anonymity.
A set of information related to this transaction is signed electronically by a double key encryption system.
The network can thus verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the content of the file, it is also possible to make sure that the exchanged bitcoins exist well in the public account book, distributed throughout the network.
The key step is to write this new transaction in this book.
It passes through the resolution of a mathematical challenge to computers, and whose winner, sort of a temporary central banker, will have the privilege of adding this additional line.
This is a phase of file hashing, that is, converting a large file into a shorter and unique digital fingerprint.
Computers "take" the new transaction and add a number to it before "hashing" the whole.
The goal is to find the number that gives a particular footprint (a lot of zeros at the beginning).
Once this number is found, the other nodes easily check that it is the right one.
The transaction is then indestructibly linked to the chain of all other transactions; any change would change the print.
If, to cheat, one user wanted to pay twice with the same money very quickly (less than ten minutes), only one of the two transactions would be validated by the network - the other remains orphaned because the two have different fingerprints.
The computer that solved the challenge wins 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, this reward is divided by two regularly, probably before the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divisible up to the one hundred millionth, which leaves margin...
The difficulty of the challenge is also raised at each increase in computing power.
The life of the network has already had ups and downs.
Websites providing services for Bitcoin have been attacked and bitcoins in stolen deposits.
"The fault used does not concern the protocol itself," says Pierre Noizat, who has just launched Paymium, a real currency payment company using the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also mentions the possibilities of money laundering through this anonymous service.
But the cash also has this flaw.
Weight actors like Wikipedia refuse gifts of this nature.
Others, like the WordPress blog platform, accept them.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron, of the Weizmann Institute in Israel, analyzed the book of accounts and showed that nearly 80% of bitcoins do not circulate.
In November, "giant balances" were launched.
"Three thousand dollars have been exchanged," says Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul, who converts bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, also the author of a teaching book on this currency, believes very much in the potential of this technology as a network of transactions.
Its system, Paytunia, is equivalent to a credit card (in real currency) or a mobile payment without contact, but it uses Bitcoin to validate transactions, which thus come back cheaper.
The carrier also manages his identity and can therefore be anonymous.
The system is easy to implement for merchants, who do not need to install new terminals or software.
All they need to do is communicate an address that a phone can "photograph and recognize," says Pierre Noizat, who assures that he has thousands of users.
There is a general movement to challenge hierarchical systems for more horizontal systems.
"It's gonna take time for Bitcoin to push itself, but 2013 could be a turning point," he predicts.
The ECB, in its report, also plans to reassess the various risks, which are now considered to be high, in the event of the success of this currency.
