A Constitution with Strengths in Egypt
This is a new poker shot by President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt remains more divided than ever around the constitutional declaration, which temporarily grants it full powers, it has decided to play its part.
Taking everyone in court, he announced on Wednesday that the Constituent Assembly would vote on its final text the following day.
Just a week ago, the Head of State gave this House two more months to complete his work.
For almost two years Egypt has been relying on a provisional text, several times amended which weakens institutional stability and leads to legal fraud.
This new initiative has only increased the fracture in the country.
For his opponents, the President perseveres in his "autocratic delusion", continuing to "translate his word" and "piestinate the law".
On the side of its supporters, it is ensured that this is a way to put an end to the institutional and political crisis as soon as possible, by accelerating the transition process.
A referendum should be held within 15 days.
A very short period of time that forces the Brothers to give up their draft to explain the text, article by article, to the Egyptians.
For the President, it is also a way to regain popular and democratic legitimacy while the challenge rages throughout the country.
Mohammed Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote in favour, as he stated in an interview with the American weekly Time.
All the more so since this use of a hasty vote owes the ultimatum to the Egyptian people: "You either vote for my text, or I keep full powers", they are supposed to end after the adoption of the Constitution.
It was in a strange atmosphere that 85 members of this Constituent Assembly, with a large Islamist majority, voted on the text yesterday.
Most Liberals were missing the call.
In mid-November, shortly before the constitutional declaration, they had slammed the door, believing that they had not been able to assert their views.
Representatives of human rights, religious minorities or civil society had done the same.
In order for the necessary quorum to be reached, 11 people, replacement members, were added in haste yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
Unsurprisingly, the articles were most often voted unanimously.
Some commentators also enjoyed the fact that one of the only differences of the day was expressed around... the hour of prayer, with some members of the committee believing that the constituent's pendulum was poorly settled.
The text, which was still being voted on last night, contains 234 articles.
The object of all the attentions, article 2 finally remains the same as that of the 1971 Constitution, stipulating that "the principles of Shariah are the main source of law."
The Salafist parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is a major claim, hoped to be able to replace "principles" with "rules", which would have allowed for stricter application.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been amended is a pledge of their goodwill and respect for the other components of Egyptian society.
"Hypocrisy", answered the Liberals, who see it only as a coup d'communication.
For according to them, the Islamization of the Constitution is done through other articles.
These include section 220, which gives Al-Azhar University an advisory role, in particular in verifying compliance with the Sharia law.
According to Egyptian expert Sophie Pommier, it is worrying because "people called to pronounce are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
You can see the firstfruits of a theocracy."
The fears of the Liberals are further exacerbated by the fact that the next rector of this university should be much less moderate than the current one.
"For the time being, there is no concrete religious involvement.
With this Constitution, we remain within the framework of the civil state.
Most of the lawyers who worked on this text are not oulemas but academics, for some trained in the French system" tempers Alexis Blouet, who prepares a thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he acknowledges "that there may be an ambiguity around article 220, because the terms used borrow from religious vocabulary.
It refers to the "fiqh" in particular [Islamic jurisprudence, ndlr].
And in the future, the question might arise as to how competent civilian judges are to decide."
Beyond its religious aspect, the text voted yesterday is highly criticized because of its extended powers to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood argues that these are significantly reduced in comparison to what they were under the former regime.
Another contentious point: the powers conferred on the army.
In accordance with the wishes of the military, the review of the defence budget will not be submitted to Parliament, but to a National Defence Council.
Nor will trials of civilians in military courts be prohibited, as called for by human rights associations.
The latter also express their concerns about the text, which they consider to be liberticide.
The crime of blasphemy is maintained and insult is now prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, including the press.
In addition, there are no more articles that reflect the protection of women, says Human Rights Watch's Heba Morayef.
In her view, the only positive point was the prohibition of torture under article 36.
The word did not appear in the previous Constitution.
While the Egyptian president had to speak on television last night, demonstrations are scheduled this afternoon.
The support of the Head of State will march them on Saturday.
In Israel, holy places, the center of the world and a sea of brine await Ukrainian tourists
The Promised Land brings together the greatness of Bible truths, modern comfort and wild nature.
Argumenty i Fakty has chosen five major reasons for going to Israel.
Go and worship the holy places
Make yourselves indispensable: the banks of the Jordan, where Jesus was baptized.
It is said that whoever enters these "baptismal funds" will be touched by the divine Grace.
As for Galilee, it is the land of Jesus' miracles: where water was changed into wine, where Jesus walked on water, where he soothed the storm, or where fishing was miraculous.
It was in this particular place that Jesus appeared before his disciples after the Resurrection.
But where you will find the most holy places, it is in Jerusalem.
Believers walk through the Rue de la Sufferance or the Way of the Cross (Latin: Via Dolorosa).
This path begins near the Antonia fortress (the pretoria), where the trial took place, then leads through the streets of the old city to the Church of the Holy Sepulchre on the Golgotha, to the place of the Crucifixion, then to the Stone of the Onction and to the tomb.
Here is the Christian center of the world, symbol of the salvation of mankind.
According to the Christian legend, the monastery of the Cross is erected at the place where the tree used to make the cross on which Jesus was crucified grew.
Jerusalem also houses the most sacred place of the Jews: the Wall of Lamentations, which constitutes the rest of a temple destroyed by the Romans in 70 B.C.
According to tradition, people of different faiths leave small words with prayers that are then answered.
Travel in height
Visit the ruins of the Massada fortress, a former refuge against enemies built by Herod the Great in 25 BC for his family.
These ruins are located on the steep rocks of a mountain 450 m above sea level.
Only mountaineering enthusiasts can go there by their own means.
For the others, a cable car takes them to this summit full of history.
In the north of the country, between 1,600 and 2,040 m of altitude, is the ski resort of Mont Hermont, which welcomes many tourists in the winter.
A shuttle can take you there from the foot of the mountain.
The ski slopes are a total of 45 km long.
Old beliefs want pagan gods to have once inhabited the top of the mountain.
Visit unique museums
This country houses nearly 300 museums.
It is impossible to visit them all during a single stay.
Here are the five most interesting ones that are really worth the detour.
First of all: the Israel Museum located near the Knesset (Parliament).
It houses the very ancient manuscripts of Qumrân, or manuscripts of the Dead Sea, discovered in the caves of the Judean Desert, as well as nearly 500 miles of archaeological and anthropological objects.
Also worth seeing: the Tel Aviv Museum of Art.
The paintings of Impressionists and Expressionists Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall and Picasso are mainly exhibited.
In Acre, the Hammam Al-Basha awaits you with its Turkish baths composed of moulds of visitors and supervisors of the time.
Once in Caesarea, enter the only private Ralli Museum where you can admire the sculptures of Rodin.
There are no guides or souvenir shops.
The entrance is free and donations are forbidden.
The fifth museum is the Museum of the Holocaust or Memorial of Yad Vashem, located in Tel Aviv, which returns to the most dramatic historical pages of history.
The most tragic part is the children's memorial, built in memory of 1.5 million children exterminated in concentration camps and gas chambers.
You enter and enter into total darkness.
Stars sparkle.
You then hear the names of Jewish children and the names of countries in which they died.
Ukraine is also mentioned.
Health and well-being
Israel's three major seaside resorts are located on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
Each offers swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and giant aquariums.
Note: you can swim in the Red Sea even in winter, as the temperature of the water does not fall below 21° while that of the air can reach 23°.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and you can swim there all year round.
By the way, it is the most unique sea in the world: it occupies the lowest point of the Earth, 417 m below sea level.
Azur-coloured water contains brine and very easily retains bathers, even those who can't swim.
The landscapes that surround it are of surreal beauty.
We come here to treat various diseases such as dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes, but also to just relax.
Discover the secrets of ancient times
They are guarded by the old town of Tel Aviv, Jaffa, on the edge of the Mediterranean Sea.
It is crossed by the famous Via Maris, which connects Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and Egyptian legends.
According to legend, it was here that Noah built his ark and that Perseus saved the beautiful Andromede, with whom he lived a long and happy life here.
Tourists especially like to walk in narrow alleys that bear the name of the signs of the zodiac.
It is said that if you touch the walls of the street corresponding to "your" sign, fate will smile at you.
In Jaffa you will be able to meet young married people who have come to take photos of all Israel and even other countries.
In Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can walk through the Roman theatre, "conquer " the fortress of the crusaders.
Under the Roman Empire, Caesarea was the main city of Judea and the residence of Roman prosecutors, including Pontius Pilate.
The carefully restored theatre is now used for evening concerts and opera performances.
Note to tourists
If you go to Israel, don't worry about your English: about 30% of the population speaks Russian.
For your trip, it is better to prefer the dollars to the euro, as they are easily exchangeable in shekels (today $1 is equivalent to 3.8 shekels).
As far as urban transport is concerned, it is mainly the buses, but Jerusalem is equipped with a fast tram and Haifa has the only metro line in the country, consisting of six stations and able to connect the lower and upper parts of the city.
It's almost an underground funicular.
The journey in all types of public transport costs 6 shekels and allows you to make changes for 1h30.
In Israel, the Jewish tradition wants to celebrate the Sabbath on Saturday.
From Friday evening to sunset on Saturday, markets, shops and public transport stop their activity.
And the workweek starts on Sunday morning.
Many cafés, restaurants and hotels serve only kosher food, which excludes pork, seafood, scaleless fish and dishes made up of both milk and meat.
It offers a multitude of dishes based on lamb and beef, soups and desserts based on coconut milk, but also houmous, traditional Jewish pasta, different sauces, balls of ground chickpeas, falafels, fruits and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs in the streets of Israeli cities.
On the other hand, there are many well-nourished cats walking around in the air.
We can see them sleeping on the roofs of parked cars in the evening.
These cats love the passing places and do not refuse to be regaled.
Car rental varies depending on the brand from $37 for 24 hours (Hyundai Getz) to $188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80).
Insurance costs $15 a day.
Renting a bike will cost you 15 shekels a day.
An entrance to the museum costs an average of 30 shekels.
The language of numbers
Three million tourists from all over the world visited Israel in 2012.
They were mostly people who came to travel and rest from the United States, Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England and Ukraine.
118.8 miles of Ukrainian tourists went to the Promised Land from January to October 2012, an increase of 51% compared to 2010, before the cancellation of the visas on 9 February 2011.
"Who has a language in Moscow goes": migrants save money to learn the language
While MPs and human rights activists are arguing about what the mandatory language test law will give, fraudsters selling "false" certificates have already made their appearance in the country
Every year, 13 million migrant workers come to Moscow, St. Petersburg and other Russian cities.
Most of the time, they are nationals of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to earn money to help their families stay at home.
Since 1 December, a law has entered into force and stipulates that every migrant worker will have to pass a Russian exam.
For the time being, this applies only to those who intend to work in the services, housing, personal services and retail sectors.
However, over time, the Federal Migration Service promises, testing will become mandatory for all immigrants.
In addition, knowledge of the language, as well as knowledge of the history of Russia and the foundations of law, will have to be validated.
You will need to validate your language skills in Russian to obtain and renew your work permit.
Only nationals of countries where Russian has official language status are exempt.
Nor are those who obtained educational certificates or diplomas prior to the fall of the USSR in 1991 affected by this law.
Benefit, negative attitude and protection of rights
The network of examination centres will be led by the Russian-language Institute Pushkin, the University of Friendship of Peoples, the Moscow State University, the State University of St. Petersburg and other higher education institutions in Russia.
Immigrants will be able to pass examinations in all the cities of the country: more than 160 centres have already been opened throughout the country.
This initiative to introduce examinations was supported by the members of the State Duma and the Federal Migration Service.
But, before the law comes into force, human rights defenders have already asked the question in the press on many occasions: what will it give?
What will the obligation to know Russian change for Russians and immigrants?
First of all, the representatives of the migration service say, this will reduce the number of people suffering "from slavery to work".
Many speak of defending the rights of migrant workers, explains the director of the office of the Russian Federal Migration Service in Tajikistan, Victor Sebelev.
The protection of rights must begin before they leave.
Only an organized selection system will solve the problems of foreign workers by 90%.
Problems arise for migrants without a profession, without training, those who do not know the language and who do not have medical certificates.
Without the understanding of the language, Sebelev certifies, the future migrant is destined to meet dishonest people who, on the pretext of helping him, will provide him with a "travel" in a crowded house where he and dozens of his fellows will be tormented for months without food and paper and will have to trim between 12 and 14 hours a day.
We receive many complaints from our migrants.
"They are promised one thing, and when they arrive, they are deceived, they are taken their passport, and they do not receive the salary they will receive," confirms Tajikistan's Head of Migration Services for the Work of the Migration Service, Tolib Charipov.
Don't argue with me, Officer!
However, many citizens of Central Asian republics who want to come and earn money in Russia trust that they do not only know the language of the country where they want to go, but also that they write with difficulty in their own language.
It is of course not their fault, but their misfortune: few Turkmens, Uzbeks, Tajiks can afford to follow even a fair primary education.
Indeed, their families do not even have enough to feed their children, not to mention to dress them properly and equip them for school.
As soon as they reach adolescence, these young people go out to earn money as soon as the opportunity arises.
It's hard when you don't know the language, trust them.
"You feel diminished and diminished."
Human rights defenders note, however, an important aspect of the language law.
The examinations will be intended only for migrants with legal status.
Without status, there will be no formal examination or work thereafter.
Yet most migrant workers continue to live illegally in Russia.
"Welcome or defense to enter"
Many immigrants explain that it is not so easy to obtain official status in Russia.
The reason? Administrative barriers and always these language difficulties.
In addition, legalization costs money: between 12 and 16 thousand rubles.
And then, you can get a fake recording quickly for only 1,500 rubles.
The Russian police know that we have false documents, that we do not have a record, hence the cases of extortion.
"They ask us 100, 200 rubles, what to buy cigarettes, tea," said the journalists Oumed Khuchkadamov, a citizen of Tajikistan.
"Do it quickly, don't hurt and buy yourself a beautiful work of art"
On the first day of the entry into force of the Language Act, it was discovered that the registration documents of migrants were not the only ones to be false.
Several false language examination certificates have already been confiscated by Federal Migration Service employees.
Falsified papers come out of an ordinary color printer.
Of course, their new owners did not have them for nothing: every migrant who hoped to make it easier for the exams had to pay seven thousand rubles for this document.
This is two and a half times more expensive than the official procedure: it will cost the migrant worker three thousand rubles.
The representatives of the government and human rights defenders agree that the short-term goal is to protect the system from corruption so that it is impossible to simply buy these "tops of paper".
The authorities may give migrant workers who have not been able to validate the examination at first the time to take language courses.
In addition, immigrants who do not know Russian will be offered work in areas that do not involve actively communicating with people.
The Ministry of the Interior does not deal with the arms market
The share of crimes involving legal weapons is very low
The Russian Ministry of the Interior proposes to tighten the law against civilian arms carriers.
This is the reaction of the authorities to recent incidents: whether it is the shootings carried out during the weddings or the killing organized by the Moscow lawyer Dmitry Vinogradov, who caused seven deaths.
The police want to ban the use of rubber bullets in public places and raise the legal age of obtaining the weapons permit from 18 to 21 years.
The idea was supported by the head of the Duma Committee on Security and Anti-Corruption, Irina Yarovaya, who promised that amendments to the Arms Act would be introduced in the State Duma in the near future.
Not everyone is happy to see that the Russian authorities are trying to solve the problem by "screwing the screw".
An open letter appeared on the Net in which its authors, representatives of various shooting centers, demanded to abandon "this senseless hardening".
The percentage of crimes committed with a registered weapon is minimal, Vasily Lesnikov, a lawyer and crime specialist for the BBC, told the Russian service.
According to statistics from the Ministry of the Interior, over a period of six months in 2012, 142 crimes were committed with a firearm registered in the police service, while 1,168 thousand crimes were recorded during the same period.
The authors of the open letter are certain that the strengthening of civil weapons laws will not prevent criminals from supplying themselves with the black market.
According to them, we can find today in Moscow any weapon for a reasonable price.
However, the Ministry of the Interior states that it controls the spread of illegal weapons.
Suppliers: from factory to officer
The black market for weapons is supplied through several channels.
The main channels are five, says Victor Baranets, retired colonel who served for ten years at the Ministry of Education and Headquarters.
Screenshot from a site taking weapons commands
The first is "the military trace", that is, the weapons that were stolen during the military operations in the Caucasus.
"These weapons were stolen by Russian officers, but also by the Caucasians," explains Baranets.
The second type of weapons from the black market are those stolen by criminals from law enforcement.
Baranets explains that these are both weapons stolen from police stocks and weapons stolen directly from law enforcement officials.
Illegal pistols go on sale from military warehouses.
Many of the latter have often suffered explosions.
"Attested versions indicate that some fires were deliberately triggered to conceal the deficit," explains the former member.
For Baranets, the weapons manufacturers are there for something.
"We see private weapons factories that do not compete with competition on the international market and leak weapons on the black market, especially in Moscow," says one expert.
One of the other sources of the black market is smuggling.
