A joint inspection by Czech and German inspectors also suggests similar conclusions.
He cites as an example of abusive practice the "Švarc system" approach by Petr Nečas.
Mr. Prime Minister recently stated that the SDG was not going to bother entrepreneurs with controls; is it allowed or prohibited?
"The law must be applied in one way or another, so if it prohibits anything, even the head of government cannot prevent an authority from acting to inspect to demand compliance with the law," Kala says.
At the meeting of the Monitoring Committee in the Chamber of Deputies, you referred to a Czech-German draft in which the laws on public procurement of these two countries were compared.
What was it really about?
This is parallel control that we launched about two years ago.
In simple terms, European legislation provides for how to manage public procurement and specific national legislation, as well as a practice itself, are followed up.
We have gathered all this and although this monitoring procedure has not yet been completed, very interesting differences have appeared to us: generally speaking, our legislation is perhaps "more stringent and of better quality", however, according to some parameters, practice as such is better in Germany.
This confirms, therefore, that it is not sufficient to draw up ever more detailed rules, but that it is necessary to devote itself to the implementation of the law itself.
How can this project help you concretely and what results for you?
This kind of joint control should help us to stop trying to clarify laws, lower and improve thresholds, when this does not have a really positive effect.
The principle of good management means getting the thing in question at a reasonable price (which does not always mean the lowest), in order to exclude any enrichment and possible criminal activity.
But by lowering market thresholds, this goal will not necessarily be achieved.
It may be that this system is so overwhelmed by paperwork that those who seek faults will find much more opportunities than if the threshold had remained higher.
You are talking about internal problems regarding the implementation of public procurement legislation.
How does the control system work in Germany?
Is there an institution similar to our CSI or a different way of organizing?
As far as the institutions, like the ISC, operate there the Bundesrechnungshof which is organized similarly, it also has a council constituted a little differently, but these two institutions proceed basically in a similar way.
The competences are also, to a certain extent, similar, but with a nuance compared to our system: Germany being a federal structure, it therefore also has rates of this type at the level of the different Länder.
The HRB can only control federal money, which corresponds to the resources of the state.
The public funds managed at home by the regions and municipalities are controlled there at the level of the Länder' accounts.
With regard to national legislation, is it simpler than ours?
I would not like to make a general comparison without concrete data, however, in some areas Germany is often referred to as a model, but surely it cannot be said that it does better in all areas.
Maybe it's because they have better inspectors?
No, I'm sure I don't, but I repeat, I don't have comparison data.
However, it must also be said that this country, which we regard as a model, is also confronted with a whole series of problems.
Otherwise they wouldn't have any advantage in cooperating with our institution, would they?
With regard to national legislation, what did the amendment of the Public Procurement Act mean to you as an institution?
As this amendment has entered into force relatively recently, it does not yet have an impact on our control operations.
As we do post-controls, we have to count on some delay.
