So do you consider the adoption of this law rather as an advantage or an additional burden on the administration?
I believe that this law is a step in the right direction and I hope that the future will confirm it.
The problem that may arise is that these rules become more stringent and that they cannot be respected.
Already under the previous regulatory regime, the provider (e.g. the Regional Council, in the case of regional operational programmes) forced the controlled subjects to accept that any violation of the Market Law signifies a breach of budgetary discipline.
Is it really helpful to make the law more severe in this way?
No, not that way, I think.
The system must exclude those who want to attack or abuse the system but not punish those who make formal mistakes without any impact on the decision-making process.
Such a system will put more pressure on administration.
So what's the solution to getting out of it?
Let's look where we're not going.
