The film Argo: when everything goes wrong, call Hollywood.
In November 1979, a crowd of protesters made up of Islamist students stormed the American Embassy in Tehran and held 52 diplomats hostage.
They were to be released in exchange for Shah, Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who, after the revolution, had fled to the United States, who had supported his regime for decades.
The situation did not offer the US administration a positive outcome, it could not, in fact, abandon the Shah, because it would have seriously shaken the confidence of its allies in other countries.
However, in Iran, where the revolution had led to the establishment of a theocratic regime, it was unable to obtain the release of hostages.
It was a hard blow to the prestige of the United States, further aggravated later by the fiasco of the attempt to release the hostages by force.
The kidnapped diplomats were finally released 444 days later, following negotiations organized by the Algerian government.
Their fate aroused a wave of solidarity and an anti-Iranian sentiment in the United States.
The Iranian debacle strongly contributed to Jimmy Carter's defeat against Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The film Argo, by actor and director Ben Affleck, describes an episode of this story that offered America a small victory.
Just before she was busy, six employees escaped from the embassy.
After complicated journeys, they found themselves in the residence of the Ambassador of Canada.
In collaboration with the Canadian authorities, the CIA managed to get them out of Iran thanks to rock-rock cover: they left the country with Canadian passports as members of a film crew who came to film a science-fiction film.
Gender combination
The plan of the exfiltration expert Tony Mendez requires the collaboration of Hollywood.
In order to make the legend more credible, specialized stores reported this film project, press conferences were organized and a fictional production company had real offices.
The details of the operation remained secret for a long time, with the film based on the memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck's film is an unusual combination of several genres.
On the one hand it is a political thriller conceived realistically but also a "caper movie", the story of a successful coup, of a betrayal - as, for example, in the trilogy Ocean'sleven, tweet and thirteen.
The ambiances follow one another: documentary-style Tehran sequences (in the subtitled sequences are presented iconic photographs of the time of events and how, thanks to these photos, these same situations were transcribed in the film, there are no great differences),
Lighter Hollywood passages, treated with irony and a bit of exaggeration,
and then scenes from CIA headquarters and other institutions with costumed men discussing the situation around conference tables, in the corridors and on the phone...
Ben Affleck managed to re-start his career in a remarkable way.
As a ridiculed actor, he became a respected director and his acting game ceased to elicit ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature film after the dark cop "Gone Baby Gone" (2007) and the thriller "The town" (2010).
It's also Affleck's first film that doesn't take place in his hometown, Boston.
The sense of a place's atmosphere is one of the characteristics that placed its first films above Hollywood standards.
Affleck also demonstrates this sense of the atmosphere in Argo where Tehran's role is "held" by Canada.
The best scenes of the film take place in streets, during the reconstruction of real facts; the initial sequence of the embassy's fall is impressive by its clarity which also suggests confusion and unpredictability occurring when suddenly, in a given place, a history page is written.
Affleck and his collaborators have a similar effect on the fictional scenes (the fake shooting team in Tehran's bazaar).
Too many shares in too many places
The director must have contented himself with a subject that actually offers only a few thrilling scenes, in the cinematic sense of the term.
He does very well, he sometimes adds some elements to reality and there, the result is not always as elegant (the scene in which the threat of crisis at Tehran airport is ruled out by a phone call in America and the pursuit on the runway is quite pulled by the hair).
Argo's weakness lies in his dissipated character, due to the need to show too many events in too many different places.
If it is true that Alan Arkin and John Goodman are quite charming in their role as Hollywood co-operators, their characters would have deserved a bigger place and they are not, far from it, the only ones in this case.
Affleck's film lacks a bit of dramatic tension, he lets himself be seen with a moderate interest, appreciating the production and retro style of the 1970s.
It trains the viewer, but with difficulty.
As a reminder of a history still, in a certain way, unfinished to date, and as an illustration of the exaggerated nature of the representation of secret services as omnipotent and omniscience, he does the job.
Rules to Inflate Balloons, Bananas and Circus
The www.bankovnipoplatky.com server, which conducts an annual public survey of the most absurd banking costs, has now decided to launch the competition for the regulation or ideas from the most absurd "EU workshop".
"The fact that the EU has been planning to adopt a 40-percent quota for the management of large European companies has led to our decision," said Patrik Nacher, the organiser of this investigation, Právo newspaper.
Among the absurdities mentioned are already, for example, the recent decision of the European Court to unify insurance premiums for men and women.
So far, however, women have been at a disadvantage in terms of life insurance rates because they objectively represent a lower risk to insurance companies.
People can report until the end of the year any other incredible idea of "the EU workshop".
"The vote will take place before the end of February 2013," Nacher said.
Among the controversial EU regulations are, for example, the obligation to add bio-components to fuels, which has adverse environmental consequences, or the ban on the use of reliable mercury thermometers, only because they contain a relatively small amount of a dangerous substance or the directive on the size of chicken cages, which has led to an increase in the price of eggs.
Criticisms have also been expressed in the past against the de facto prohibition of using the term "butter to spread" or the withdrawal of the sale of conventional bulbs.
Quality bananas must be 14 centimetres in size.
The European administration often reacts under pressure from a commercial or industrial lobby whose applications are usually defended in Brussels by a State or group of States (as well as the Czech Republic currently imposes the requests of its banks by threatening to use its right of veto).
For example, the interests of pressure groups are also at the root of the fact that in the Union bananas must not be smaller than 14 cm in size or have an "abnormal curvature".
The European Commission defended itself by arguing that it was merely harmonising non-homogeneous national standards that complicated trade.
Fruit and vegetable standards have been relaxed despite opposition from some States, claiming that the existing directives result in food waste.
The first prize may be awarded in this investigation to last year's EU regulation that should include a warning on inflatable balloons that children under the age of 8 should not inflate without adult supervision.
The EU referred to an American investigation that balloons are, among toys, the leading cause of child suffocation deaths.
A similar restriction applies to children under the age of 14 in terms of blowing in fair trumpets.
We have weird ideas here, too.
The following rule concerning European civil servants themselves is quite absurd: because of the sensitivity of this theme for Greece, anyone with an official function within the EU cannot use the name "Macedonia" and should instead speak of FYROM (Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia).
In collaboration with the "Laissez Faisse" association of liberal economists, the server Bankovnípoplatky.com has appointed in this investigation, in addition to some of the absurdities mentioned above, the Union Regulation on the volume of food reserves in the territory of the Czech Republic.
The EU had set maximum volumes for food reserves that could be found in the territory of the Czech Republic on the day of our accession to the EU.
The Czech Republic then exceeded, for example, the fixed volumes for canned mushrooms and therefore faced a heavy fine.
The organizers of this survey found it interesting to pay money to some countries because they do not have access to the sea and the idea of granting a grant to apply for subsidies.
These ideas, however, are not from Brussels but from Prague.
"The fact that we don't have a sea handicaps us.
We will ask the European Union for a refund". Thus expressed, in autumn 2004, the Minister of Agriculture of the time Jaroslav Palas (ČSSD).
He argued that, as a result of our wheat production, and following the so-called "interventionist" purchases, the state had found itself with full stocks that it had then had to export.
According to Palas, the EU should have paid us millions of euros, because the Czech Republic is far from ports.
In the end, the European Commission responded positively to the Czech demand and organised a call for tenders for the purchase of wheat from countries without maritime access.
Grants for grants were proposed to the municipalities by the Ministry of Local Development headed by Minister Pavel Němec (US-DEU), which were to be used, in practical terms, to draft grant applications granted by Brussels.
The EU states: "Strange regulations are rare".
While regulations often raise criticism in the Member States, according to many experts, the EU's efforts to regulate and improve the effectiveness of the functioning of the Union and in the field of its general development deserve praise.
More serious, for example, according to experts, is the problem of the use of EU grants for projects that have absolutely nothing to do with strengthening European integration, but which were imposed by the Member States during the budgetary negotiations.
