The architects of the MVRDV firm prove that true adventures are not just a matter of imagination. To convince yourself, just look at Spijkenisse and the newly erected mountain of books - 2 photos
"I think this building is funny, it makes very futuristic, finally something interesting to see," says Lisette Verhaig, a passer-by on the lower side of the street.
Stefan Spermon, a computer scientist in a large nearby company, tells us: "Yes, it is indeed very beautiful, this building".
But I wonder why we still need a library today.
Everyone has Internet, an iPad and e-books.
Now, no one's going to one of these sloppy libraries of their own free will anymore, is it?
Spijkenisse, a dormitory town that has nothing to do with the gates of Rotterdam, holds a rather special record.
The municipality of 80,000 souls has the lowest education rate in the Netherlands.
In order to restore some neurons to the brains, the city decided, a few years ago, to contribute to the general culture and to reproduce the seven fictitious bridges that appear on the euro banknotes in the form of beautiful miniatures in painted reinforced concrete.
The success of the cultural offensive has remained limited.
This is how the city authorities realized that there was only one way to get back to the statistics: the construction of a library!
Winy Maas, of the architectural office of Rotterdam MVRDV, master of diagrams in bold sticks and creator of buildings full of mind and often cynical, accepted the project with his usual phlegm and presented himself to the competition in 2003 with five books under his arm and a sneezing on his face.
And while the jury members were still looking at each other, bewildered and raising their shoulders, Maas, the faceless, piled up his books of choice in order of size to make it a pyramid, and ended his discourse supported by activist arguments by a "common love!"
Here it is, my proposal for the mountain of books of Spijkenisse, or as they say, the Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the 30 million-euro mountain came out of land.
The building is part of a revitalization project that also includes underground parking, a supermarket, a post office and a few buildings and houses for a total of 50 houses.
In early November, the mountain of books received the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012".
In addition, the project was selected for the Dutch National Wood Award 2012.
Thus, this dull little town, which until now had nothing more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian zone and a town hall of a disgusting ugliness, whose white facades invite to think that they are home to a dairy, has enriched itself with a contemporary architectural work.
The most important thing is that Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in its history.
The long way to reading
First impression: Eldorado of the book under cheese bell.
Certainly, an elevator takes you to the heart of the massif, but the true joys of reading and architecture open to you when you trample the floor of the building to discover its topography.
The interior entirely made of glass is bright and clear, the Dutch brick floor and elegant reverbers speak unequivocally the language of municipal public squares.
The urban atmosphere is perfect.
We're already looking for public benches, dogs and little boys and girls who play ball.
And books, books and books everywhere.
"Normally, the library shelves are located along the façade and in the middle there is a large and dark room, which is often uncomfortable and impersonal," explains Willy Maas.
We completely disrupted the classical spatial configuration and opened the reading spaces from the inside to the outside.
The interior of the mountain of books has been tastefully arranged: in the middle are the offices, the Internet library, the chess club, the center for the environment and the technical center of the building.
A particular beauty lies in the black rays of the library, which are sometimes wall tiles, sometimes balustrades, sometimes stairwells.
A new experience for sight, touch and smell.
Even the architects and engineers of the hardened building do not want unknown materials.
"We wanted to work with recycled materials," explains Joop Trouborst, project manager at the municipality of Spijkenisse, in a response to the Standard.
For example, one day we found an ad hoc waste from agriculture in an agricultural enterprise.
In the Netherlands, one millimetre thick synthetic membrane has been used for years as a substrate in greenhouses and fields.
It's cheap, and we're saving time.
The thin membrane is used for one or two seasons, then it can be discarded.
For the library, the membrane was compressed, for the first time in such quantities, into plates four centimetres thick.
Under the influence of heat and pressure, the "Landbouwplastic " (KPL) changes color and turns into a dark, homogeneous and resistant material, the smell of which evokes both a new car and sports shoes.
At the top of the 105 steps is the top of the mountain.
After almost 500 meters, the literary café offers a breathtaking view of the city, but also Dutch croquettes and ficus in pots.
The latter create an atmosphere, but they contribute mainly to the maintenance of the ideal level of air humidity in the literary mountain.
Gifts for the New Soul
"It's incredible, but despite all the glass surfaces, this building is a model project in terms of ecology," says Trouborst.
The temperature of the building is adjusted by geothermal temperature.
Although the mountain of books is below a glass bell, the sun only illuminates the interior for a short time, even on days of good weather.
The thick wooden beams mounted from across the glass facade serve as a sunscreen, intercepting a large part of the rays.
The atmosphere is very pleasant.
Completely automated blinds take care of the rest.
Stefan Spermon, the septic informatician mentioned above, has already risked entering the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was already there.
Cynthia Bogarde, a professor of traditional Chinese medicine, even describes Boekenberg as the "soul finally found" of Spijkenisse.
A few weeks ago, at the inauguration, every citizen was invited to donate a book from his personal library.
This has made it possible to fill the gaps in the library that was not yet fully filled (today it has 70,000 books).
The concept is a success.
The rays are all over the place.
For architect Winy Maas, "there's nothing worse than a half-empty library."
"I believe that our invitation has created a certain relationship between every citizen and this new building.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
Even if it's only for decoration."
This is how MVRDV has reached the master discipline that is called, in professional jargon, "the creation of an identity".
Spijkenisse wrote a new page in literary history.
Even though she may seem young and uneducated.
Finally, it is a new starting point for the birth of an identity.
Szabo: "Germans must play a greater role."
Germany chose forbearance during the vote on the admission of the Palestinian State.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on relations between the United States and the EU, this decision puts Berlin in a difficult political situation.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week, Germany had announced its intention to vote against the Palestinian request for observer status with the United Nations.
But then she chose forbearance.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not approve of what the Israelis did in Gaza.
However, Berlin must be cautious, as it maintains special relations with Israel.
But I also think that it does not support the American position either.
Germany wanted to assert its independence, but not to be too critical of Israel.
During the March 2011 insurgency in Libya, Germany also chose to abstain in the vote on the establishment of an no-fly zone.
Finally, NATO imposed this measure.
Is it difficult for Germany to adopt a clear position on major international issues?
The answer is yes.
The reason for this is that Berlin is reviewing its foreign policy, seeking to move away from a policy so to speak defined by the Americans and to establish a German foreign policy.
Moreover, the lack of a coherent and common policy within the Union complicates the situation.
The Germans therefore face several fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they're still trying to find that role, but they're on the road to a "more normal" foreign policy.
Foreign policy, such as in France or Great Britain
What, then, does the term "normal" foreign policy mean to the Germans?
It shows the willingness to adopt positions independent of those of the United States and European partners, including with regard to national files.
I believe that German foreign policy is also determined by its economic policy, therefore by exports and its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany's economic interests are, to a certain extent, different from those of the other major powers, which is why Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced Germany's position vis-à-vis the Middle East conflict and forbearance during the United Nations vote?
Germany first has important markets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf countries.
That is why Berlin must be careful not to clash with public opinion, but also with the elites of the Arab countries.
This is undoubtedly a determining factor.
However, I would not attach too much importance to it, because it is not an exclusively unilateral relationship.
But this is in any case a decisive element in German strategic thinking.
Does Germany undermine its relations with the United States by choosing forbearance in important votes, as in the case of Palestine?
I think that Europeans and Americans understand the German position perfectly.
That is why I think the fracture is not so serious that it was in the case of the Libyan question.
Perhaps even Germany will be more respected.
Indeed, Germany has shown that it must be taken seriously as an international actor and that its interests must be taken into account.
In Europe, opinions on the Palestinian initiative are diverse.
On the other hand, the United States announced its veto with a clear voice.
Do opinions differ between the United States and the majority of European countries?
There have always been differences because of the American domestic political scene.
I believe that the Obama Administration is secretly showing great understanding of the European position.
But given the country's political configuration, the government cannot, of course, defend its position publicly.
I believe that the real differences of opinion are not so great that they always seem to be.
If you look at the relationship between Obama and Israeli Prime Minister Netanyahu, you will notice that Obama is far from enthusiastic about Netanyahu's policy.
Does Germany find it difficult to reconcile its close relations with Israel and the United States, on the one hand, with the position of the major European partners, on the other?
I don't think it makes it any easier for the Germans.
Of course, it would be a little simpler for the Germans if there was a coherent and uniform European policy, but today it is not.
They cannot, therefore, join a broader political line and must affirm their unique position.
This is what they are currently doing in the question of the euro.
In my opinion, Germany will play a locomotive role in the future and will push Europe to adopt a European position.
It is not simple for Germany, especially because of relations with Israel.
This issue has always been a sensitive one.
But in my view, the Germans are well aware of the fact that they must play a role that more marks their independence.
Does Germany see itself playing a major role on the international stage, does Germany only want to play a key role?
Or is it still difficult to assume leading roles?
Germany is still not used to it, it is always uncomfortable and, for obvious reasons, the country still has difficulties in playing a more important role.
If we look, for example, at the euro crisis, we notice that every time Germany decides to weigh more, many anti-German feelings are heard.
It doesn't make it any easier for the Germans.
In fact, it is always the same problem: we do not want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
From this point of view, Germany is in a much more delicate position than the United States.
It has to deal with very diverse neighbors and opinions, and it is not easy.
Today, the influence of the United States on European policy is only diminishing, but at the moment, the EU is not filling this gap, so who is left?
The Germans will simply have to play a more important role.
And even if they don't like it, even if it's unpleasant to them and if they're only less appreciated, it's life!
Stephen Szabo is the Deputy Director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, where academics and political experts from Europe and North America jointly analyse the challenges of the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he specializes in German politics, American foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
"Brand protection" in China: when Puma and Armani suddenly become Chinese
Armani and Polo Ralph Lauren are well-known brands around the world.
Armani Polo... what is this really about?
Behind this name is a trademark officially registered in China, but which has nothing to do with the original company.
The trade mark thus enjoys protection such that the undertaking bearing the name of the trade mark cannot lodge a complaint.
And even if she could, he's not sure she'd get a win.
"It is becoming increasingly difficult for foreigners to protect their brands in China," explains Thomas Pattloch, a lawyer at Taylor Wessing's office specializing in violation of property rights in the Far East.
Every week, a new file arrives on my desk.
Impersonators only need a few additional letters to be able to register their brands.
For example, instead of Gucci, Lu-Gucci is recorded, and instead of Prada, Prada-Kny is recorded.
German companies are also legally copied, such as Puma, the manufacturer of sports articles.
