Facts about sexually transmitted infections
What are the most common sexually transmitted diseases?
Bacterial STIs include syphilis, chlamydia and blennorragia (or gonorrhea).
Common STIs are HIV, human papillomavirus, genital herpes or hepatitis.
Pubis lice and scabs belong to parasitic STIs.
Which groups are mainly concerned?
Syphilis and blennorragia often occur in men who have sex with other men.
The Robert-Koch Institute estimates that sexual contact between men is responsible for at least four out of five cases of syphilis reported in Germany.
In heterosexual adults, chlamydia-related infections, trichomonase, candidiasis (fungal), blennorragia and human papilloma virus are common sexually transmitted diseases.
The rate of spread of HIV among heterosexual adults is relatively low in Germany. However, some 20% of new HIV infections are observed in this group.
In young people, there is a significantly higher rate of chlamydia-related infections than in other population groups.
According to European surveys, three-quarters of all infections concern young people between the ages of 15 and 25.
Moreover, in Germany, the human papillomavirus is common among young people.
What is the evolution of the number of infections?
It is not mandatory to report all sexually transmitted diseases.
According to the Robert-Koch Institute, the number of cases of syphilis has more than doubled in 10 years: the figure has increased from 1,967 in 2001 to 3,698 in 2011.
Since 2007, the number of new HIV infections has declined.
In 2011, there were approximately 2,700 cases.
This represents a decrease of one tenth from the previous year.
What are the symptoms of a sexual disease?
Infectious diseases can cause abscesses in the genital organs, urinary pain, white discharges, lower belly pains, and the appearance of buttons and warts.
However, they do not regularly cause any pain or other symptoms and thus remain hidden.
How can we protect ourselves?
Condoms may reduce the risk of infection, but they do not protect 100%.
The reason for this is that sexually transmitted disease pathogens can also be transmitted by lubricating infection or by close body contact.
The experts therefore recommend that anyone who often changes sexual partners undergo regular examinations.
Most rapidly detected STIs can be cured and late sequelae can be avoided.
