The toughest job in the world: Kawah Ijen's human mules
For four euros, Indonesian volcano-bearers risk their lives and health by carrying 70 kilos of sulphur across steep stone paths.
There are people for whom work is hell and others who literally work in hell.
This is the case of Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 miners who earn their living wearing the sulfur of the Kawah Ijen volcano, east of the Indonesian island of Java.
It must work every day to the bottom of the crater, where the sulphuric gas from the earth's insides solidifies in contact with the air.
After collecting large sulphur rocks, which weigh about 70 kilos in total, he installs them in two bamboo baskets which he loads on his shoulders through the steep trails.
There are only 250 meters to the top of the volcano that peaks at 2,386 meters of altitude, but exhausted carriers take more than 40 minutes to climb this distance, at a turtle's appearance, keeping the balance and measuring their steps so as not to stumble and fall into the precipice.
They know that a false step could cost them their lives, as happened to a French tourist who made a fatal fall in the Kawah Ijen volcano several years ago.
The miners of Kawah Ijen earn 5 cents of euro for each kilo of sulphur extracted.
Once at the top, a path is paved between tourists who photograph them as if they were circus beasts, and carrying the heavy baskets painfully, they walk the 3 kilometers until the balance that a mining company has installed a little below at 1,850 meters of altitude.
This is PT Candi Ngrimbi, a company that has operated the volcano since 1960 and, as we can tell, its employees, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 cents of euros) per kilo of sulphur.
It then sells it to the petrochemical industry at 10,000 rupees (83 cents euro) since this ore is very present in everyday life and is used to make candles, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even to bleach sugar.
"As we transport about 70 kilos, we earn about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) per trip," explains Anto, who usually makes three trips a day.
Each one takes 3 hours and ends up exhausted, but this allows him to earn 138,000 rupees (11.50 euros) at the end of the day.
Although this seems to be a misery for such a superhuman effort, it is three times what he would gain in the fields.
"The income of minors is very high here, where the coffee harvest is paid 15,000 rupees (1.20 euros) per day and where the average monthly wage is 2 million rupees (167 euros)", says the porter who used to work as a bricklayer on the tourist island of Bali.
There, his salary was 75,000 rupees (6.20 euros) per day and the job was not as difficult, but Anto returned to his family in Banyuwangi, a village close to the volcano, for a reason which, in Indonesia, is as unquestionable as sulphur: "I married a girl from Bali, where they are Hindus, and I brought her back to Java to convert to Islam".
Anto suffers from asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs constantly and his eyes are irritated by toxic gases.
At the age of 27, he spent three of his life defying the danger on the Kawah ljen, but the sulfur has already begun to make him pay the bill although he covers his face with a mask and wears special gloves.
Anto suffers from asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs constantly and his eyes are irritated by the toxic gases released by the volcano.
That's the price he has to pay to pursue his dream.
"I'm going to work another two years, because I want to open a shop or study Spanish or French," he promises in an English more than acceptable.
Life-ridden, this friendly and intelligent young man could be a tourist guide, waiter or receptionist in a hotel, but instead he does the work of a mule.
It shares an unhealthy wooden masura with other carriers, rises every day at two o'clock in the morning because the sulphur keeps pouring out at night, when its characteristic yellow color becomes blue and shines in the middle of darkness.
Defying the darkness, Anto descends into the crater with a small lamp attached to his helmet, which he bought himself with his own money.
Some 400 carriers load the sulphur baskets on their shoulders from the bottom of the crater.
Despite its comfortable profits, the mining company did not mechanize the extraction of sulphur to save costs and does not provide any equipment to the carriers who work on their own and are paid by weight.
In addition, they do not touch a sub of the 30,000 rupees (2.50 euros) increase per camera, in addition to the entrance of 15,000 rupees (1.20 euros), that the guards of this natural park charge tourists who come to photograph the volcano and its human mules.
"This work is done for beasts, not for humans," protested Madrusin, a 42-year-old porter who has been working in Kawah Ijen for thirty years, since he left college.
Capable of carrying up to 110 kilos, he assures that he will not stop working "as long as he can", because he needs money to raise his 3 sons, aged between 10 and 18.
I won't retire, I'll die here because the volcano is my whole life.
