The Unasur Summit ended without the Lima Declaration being made public
The Sixth Presidential Summit of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) ended today in Peru without the Lima Declaration being made public, although it was previously announced and theoretically adopted by the 7 representatives present.
Efe has repeatedly tried to access the document signed at the 6th Ordinary Meeting of Heads of State and Government of Unasur, but the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and the Presidency initially reported that it would be released after the summit was closed, and then said that it would be published from time to time on the Peruvian government's website.
When asked about the text, they reported that its contents had been presented by the President of Peru, Ollante Humala, in brief statements to the press.
Journalists' access to information about the summit has been constantly limited.
During the day, only the video without the sound of the presidential assembly with the message "private session, restricted audio" was broadcast in the press room.
The lack of information among journalists was reported by press officers from some of the Unasur governments who attended the meeting, with the exception of the Peruvian spokesman.
The only document released during the day was the list of presidents present, which caused some discomfort among the hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who demanded more important information.
Later, the Presidency of Peru sent an e-mail to the media with the "final declaration" of the summit, but it was President Humala's speech and not the official document that concluded the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the 3rd Arab South American Summit (ASPA) and, on that occasion, although it was requested by the press, it had also not disseminated the statement also called the Lima Declaration, as previously announced.
On the official ASPA website, it can be verified that the document was published last March.
At the two international meetings, the Peruvian authorities tried to put in place secure transmission systems for all journalists, but they limited the maximum amount of information.
The summit also concluded with the joint agreement of Chile and Peru to accept a judgment of the Court of The Hague which decides a different border between the two countries.
The Presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and of Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met at the regional meeting and stated that they would respect the decision of the ICJ to hear the pleas of both parties in the trial that Lima brought against Santiago and that begins Monday in The Hague.
"We will respect and enforce the verdict that will resolve the disputes that we are bringing today before this international court," said President Humala, alongside his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile has always been, and will continue to be, a country that respects international law, the peaceful resolution of disputes, treaties and international tribunals," added President Piñera, giving a hand to President Humala, alongside the flags of both countries.
The confirmation of the two presidents that they would submit to the ICJ took place after Colombia denounced this week the Bogota Pact by which it had agreed to submit to the decisions of this international tribunal, after a decision on the maritime boundaries with Nicaragua which it considered to be gravely wrong.
The summit was held without the presence of the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff, Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, Bolivia, Evo Morales, and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, suspended from Unasur since 2011, after the dismissal of its former president Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the meeting.
The host president, Ollanta Humala, was tasked with opening the deliberations in the morning and closing the summit shortly after noon in Lima.
The representative read the final document in which he announced that 16 agreements had been adopted and that the lines of action of 31 projects had been set between South American countries for a total of $17 million in investment.
Among the agreements adopted, he mentioned that the Unasur countries would put in place "significant steps to achieve the goal of South American citizenship through the development of agreements on residence permits".
He informed that action would be taken to improve "cooperation in the fight against urban insecurity and international organized crime, actions to improve access to medicines, low-cost Internet access in all of South America, and to jointly and effectively assess the risks of natural disasters".
With a Europe in crisis, "the economic consolidation (of Latin America) must not have a triumphalist matrix but must help to increase our productive matrix and to look forward to a better future for our populations," concluded President Humala.
"We have decided to focus on a group of 31 iconic projects that improve the connection of South American spaces, especially in rural and border areas... by uniting our countries and generating new economic circuits," said the Peruvian President in a speech.
Among these projects, he mentioned that five were concerned with Peru and were on the transversal axes of his territory, from the coast to Brazil, and that two were aimed at a more important connection with Ecuador, although he did not provide further details.
Similarly, the final document mentions the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that this country's electoral process will allow its reintegration into the Union of South American Nations", from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of prosperity and peace, integrated and having good relations with its neighbours, is another theme addressed at the summit.
In this sense, the Colombian President, Juan Manuel Santos, said, before starting the regional meeting, that he hoped to meet his Nicaragua counterpart, Daniel Ortega, the following Saturday in Mexico City to discuss calmly the maritime dispute through a judgment of the ICJ requested by Bogota.
"It is possible that tomorrow (Saturday), I have a meeting with President Daniel Ortega," said President Santos.
"We're going to review all these avenues, they're not exhaustive, including the treaty with Nicaragua that's going to ask for a discussion with that country," he said.
"I hope to be able to tell President Ortega that we are going to settle this in the most civilized and respectful way possible," said President Santos.
Presidents Santos and Ortega will meet Saturday in Mexico City where they plan to attend the inauguration of the new president of this country, Enrique Peña Nieto.
Similarly, within the framework of the summit, the Defence Ministers of the bloc will meet in advance to approve the 2013 Action Plan, which seeks to strengthen dialogue and consensus in terms of defence in the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay are members of Unasur, although the latter country is suspended.
Peru holds the pro tempore presidency of the regional bloc.
