AIDS-related deaths are now due to late detection.
Fabrizio was 21 when he was confirmed the test result: HIV positive.
"It was as if the sky had fallen on my head," he said, referring to the time of the announcement, that the doctor had tried to make "less painful", in vain.
The young man hid it from his family.
He decided to take care of his illness on his own and began to inquire about it and his hard work was such that he had just celebrated his 43rd birthday.
He is undoubtedly one of the oldest patients in the HIV unit of the Civil Hospital of Guadalajara (HCG), in which he met in 1994 after many battles.
Fabrizio has been living with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) for 22 years, something difficult to imagine in the early 1990s, where there were many doubts, few treatment choices and more stigmas.
So even the director of an IMSS clinic avoided saying goodbye to him "because he was speechless."
At that time, having AIDS was synonymous with death.
Today, it is possible to survive this syndrome and to have a good quality of life.
However, ignoring their disease, many people still arrive when the virus has already caused damage, "exhaust" their immune system and are victims of opportunistic infections.
31 years after the emergence of AIDS in the world, in any case after the first reported cases, "the great victory today is that the survival of a patient who started treatment at the right time and the survival of the general population is exactly the same," said the head of the HCG HIV Unit, Jaime Andrade Villanueva and he takes as a reference that this information was validated in April of this year in a prestigious scientific publication.
The HIV/AIDS infectiologist and expert, Andrade Villanueva, commented that since 2008, scientists have concluded that AIDS is no longer a fatal disease, but that the number of years of survival and quality of life depend on the level of allocation of the immune system presented by patients at the time of diagnosis, with better prospects for those who do not use drugs: up to 30 years for a CD4 rate of 200 and up to 50 years for those who reach 500 CD4.
To speak simply, this means that for someone who would receive a positive HIV diagnosis at 25 years of age, "as long as he remains under control, he will be able to live without problems up to 75 years of age," said the scientist interviewed.
In order to put this progress in context, it is important to know that the life expectancy of Mexicans is now on average 76 years.
While mortality has decreased significantly in recent years, in the case of Mexico, the number of AIDS-related deaths increased from 6,678 in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (according to the UNAIDS annual report), but it is also true that, since the onset of AIDS, 60% of the patients identified on the national data base have died.
Just in Jalisco, 255 people died in 2011, and there were 187 deaths until May of this year; however, we are assured that access to antiretroviral drugs has been universal since 2005.
Then why are there still deaths?
I don't think the problem is with access to treatment.
That's how I see it, that's what happened in our hospital.
Over the past 12 years or so, we've never been without medicines, the problem is that patients get to very advanced stages because they don't know they're infected, or they learn it at advanced stages of the disease.
It gives us an indisputable fact "nine in ten patients arrive when they already have an opportunistic infection, what it takes to have a greater impact on overall mortality, is to make earlier diagnoses and, for this, it is necessary to offer screening tests in a massive way, to all those who request it".
The specialists and members of the Jalisco (Coesida) State AIDS Prevention Council agree on his proposal, as well as the patients themselves, such as Fabrizio, who had to take his screening test in a private laboratory, simply because a friend had done it and despite his young age, he was already carrying AIDS and suffering from Kaposi's sarcoma, a cancerous tumor that is one of the common complications.
Everything changes when you learn you have AIDS.
Some people think they're going to die and don't want to know anything.
"If I'm going to die, I'd better have a good three times a week," they say, "it's not my case.
Change has been beneficial, I eat well, I exercise, I take my medication.
To date, his parents only know that he has cancer.
I have a normal life, like anyone else.
"I work, I have a lot of activities, I travel, I have an active sex life, but co-responsible, I pay attention to myself and the other person," says Fabrizio, who agreed to share his intimacy with MILENIO JALISCO to help, thanks to his testimony, those who are afraid today, during the march of World AIDS Day.
Let them take the test, if they have taken risks, the sooner they will know if they are HIV-positive and the better it will be, and if they already have the diagnosis, they must know that we can live like everyone else, being responsible.
His message summarizes the slogan of the battle against AIDS in this year 2012.
Condoms on the counter
There are many gaps between health programmes and the ordinary citizen, says Ricardo Salazar, Guadalajara journalist who embraced the cause of HIV.
And the greatest is prevention.
In all places dedicated to this, "we have actually increased the distribution of condoms, before we were given one or two, now we are given a hundred packets, it is very good, but it results, that still today, some do not have access to condoms," he says.
Adolescents are among the most vulnerable to new infections.
The question: "What are you going to do with it?", posed with sarcasm and value judgments by social workers, guidance counselors, pharmacists and health professionals, is the question that teenagers do not want to hear, says the journalist.
It proposes to reorient this ineffective distribution; that condoms not only be sold at counters, but are found in public toilet dispensers and in places frequented by young people.
It is not about encouraging promiscuity.
Nor is it a question of paying for the girls and the motel, as Governor Emilio González had said when asked if there would be a distribution of condoms in his administration.
"It's not how sexuality works, it's best to provide condoms to people who are already sexually active," he said.
The figures in Jalisco
There are 13.435 cumulative cases (12.158 AIDS and 1.317 HIV).
The State is the 4th state of the country in number of new and cumulative AIDS cases and 13th in number of HIV patients.
92% of the contamination is by sex, 6% by blood and 2% by perinatal route.
It is estimated that 50,000 people live with HIV, since for each recorded case there are 4 or 5 people who do not know it.
A judgment ratified on appeal by a United States court ignores the restructuring of the Vitro Group's debt through commercial bankruptcy in Mexico. The scenario causes a bad precedent for all domestic companies with branches in the neighbouring country and with solvency problems.
It seems, therefore, that the procedures for the survival of companies authorized by Mexican laws are not valid in the country under the starry banner, contrary to international agreements.
From a practical point of view, the blow to the judgment rendered on 15 June by Judge Harlin Hale of the Court of Bankruptcy for the Northern District of Texas leaves Mexican companies defenceless in the face of the possibility of embargoing their properties beyond Bravo.
However, the resolution will allow Mexico's main glass manufacturer to appeal to the U.S. Supreme Court based on three inconsistencies.
First, while the judge of the case points out that creditors must register under the United States Bankruptcy Act, the Fifth Circuit Appeal Court, sitting in New Orleans, claims that the main proceeding is formalized commercial bankruptcy in Mexico.
The first point would involve denouncing international procedural cooperation in insolvency cases involving companies with a transnational profile.
In fact, the United Nations Model Law for Uniform International Commercial Law had been created for that purpose by taking the American Law Institute as an arbitrator.
Secondly, the judgment states that without the inter-company vote, recognised in the critical mass of commercial bankruptcy, the debts contracted by Vitro's subsidiaries to the parent company, the majority required for the approval of the restructuring could not have been obtained.
However, Mexican laws recognize this possibility.
In fact, Vitro's case is not the first to use this plan.
Here there are half a dozen examples, among them Agremex and Comercial Mexicana, whose Federal Institute of Commercial Bankruptcy had secured debts.
Moreover, what is certain is that, since the subsidiary votes remained, in all ways Vitro's creditors who fought against this in the US courts, i.e. the "value" funds such as Aurelios Capital, Aurelios Convergence, Elliot Internacional and Liverpool Limited, would not have obtained the majority.
The vote would have been 45 to 37.
Data omitted by the Court of Appeal.
On the other hand, Vitro was blamed for the difficult situation he had faced since 2008 without stopping at the severe economic crisis faced by the United States, affecting the country's costs.
For the time being, the Gonzalez Sada family company will appeal to the same appeal court for the vote to be held in its entirety, i.e. with the five magistrates, since only three had voted.
The insurance action will demand non-prosperity and require a review of the trial by a higher court, in this case the U.S. Supreme Court of Justice.
The most serious is that the court ignored a document sent by the Government of Mexico on behalf of the amicus curiae ("friend of the Court") in which Vitro's procedure under the Commercial Bankruptcy Act was detailed, noting that this freed him from the conventions signed by the two countries to bring it to the same level as paragraph 15 of the United States Bankruptcy Act.
In addition, he noted that the country had adhered to the principles of the United Nations Commission on International Trade, i.e. the rules established for cross-border insolvency cases, which ensured fairness for debtors and creditors.
Two-part carambolage: they astonish Vitro and they astonish the country.
