Hector "Hetin" Reyes "Basketball is my whole life"
The globe-trottor of the basketball "Hetin" Reyes spent more than 60 years of his life in relation to the field and, thanks to it, traveled all over the world.
Few people in Puerto Rico have a knowledge of the history of local basketball as big as Hector "Hetin" Reyes.
The reason for this is that before a brain hemorrhage sentenced him to wheelchair in 2008, Reyes was immersed in this sport for more than 60 years, whether as a lower league player, a national basketball team player, a national team manager and leader, the BSN, with the Bayamón Vaqueros or as president of the basketball federation.
"I wore several caps in basketball throughout my life, and even several at the same time, as when I was president of the BSN, director general of the national team and president of the federation during the 90s," Reyes recalls during a visit of Primera Hora to his home in Bayamón, where he resides with Isabel, his faithful wife for over 50 years.
"Basketball is my whole life."
Reyes does not exaggerate when he makes that statement.
The walls of his house, almost all decorated with photos and memories that remind us of his extraordinary itinerary, testify to this.
Bayamón in the heart
Of all his memories, those he loves most are those who remind him of his passing as a player in the Vaqueros team in the mid-50s until 1982, after spending 15 years as a co-manager or manager of the team.
"It was my best years, the ones I enjoyed most because I had the chance to participate in eight Vaqueros championships from 1967, whether as manager, co-manager or leader.
This has been a great many years of satisfaction, including the five championships held from 1971 to 1975.
I then retired from the championship in 1981, the year Jerome Mincy joined the BSN team.
From there, "Cuco" Ortiz, who was a great administrator, took the lead of the team," says Reyes.
I remember Gene Bartow, who had been a leader here and who was at the University of Alabama (Birmingham), told me: "I have a strong player for you, he is two meters tall.
Do you want it?"
This is how to start Mincy, one of the best players Puerto Rico has had.
Bartow then recommended me Raymond Gausse, who was naturalized and who was one of the best shooters.
I remember he said that if Mincy had allowed Bayamon to win a championship, Gausse would help us try to win another one.
He was delighted with the Vauqueros championship with Gausse, but only remotely since in 1988 he was already the great mannitou of the federation.
At that time, he preferred to take advantage of his duties and those of Mincy on the national team.
I remember when we won it for the first time in the United States during the pre-Olympic tournament in Mexico City in 1989.
Then there was the 1990 World Cup, where we got 4th and where we should have won the bronze medal if that Canadian judge hadn't let us play the last game again, Reyes said.
Is the 1990 World Cup team the best national team you've ever seen?
She is one of the best, just like the one who beat the Dream Team at the 2004 Olympic Games.
But my favorite is that of the Cuban Pan American Games in 1991, when we won the gold and beat the United States team, which was quite similar to the one that won the bronze at the World Cup.
This team was not only composed of Mincy, Gausse, Ramon Rivas, Fico López and "Piculín" (Ortiz), there were also the young (Javier) "Toñito" Colón and James Carter, the brothers León (Francisco and Edgar) and Mario "Quijote" Morales, who had not been able to attend the 90th World Cup due to a knee problem.
A team that may not have been the best in terms of individuals, but it gave us a gold medal and great joy during the Neuquén pre-Olympic tournament in Argentina.
With players like "Canito" Nieves, Pablo Alicea and the young Rolando Hourruitiner replacing the players suspended by the imbroglio of the Pan American Games of Mar del Plata, we won the gold against all the prognostics.
What was Puerto Rico's best player?
Without a doubt, this is Piculín Ortiz.
His statistics at the international tournament level are impressive.
No one in Puerto Rico has dominated this level as Piculin did.
And that doesn't take into account his trajectory in the different leagues he played for.
Who was the best Puerto Rican leader?
It's very hard to say.
We had a good team composed of Julio Toro, Flor Meléndez, Carlos Morales, Raymond Dalmau, Armandito Torres.
In young people, I really like the work Leo Arill does.
For you, what is your greatest success in the federation?
To have been part of the most glorious time of the national team between 1988 and 1995, and the fact that in the early 1990s the BSN had up to 17 teams in one season.
What's left for you to do?
There are things I would have liked to put in place, such as the regionalization of the minor categories.
For example, Ponce's boys play only in their area and face only teams from other corners of the island during national playoffs.
Today, young people travel and play too much while this is not necessarily necessary.
At least I saw the advantage of mandatory certifications and courses for leaders, field staff and arbitrators.
It makes me happy.
What are you doing today?
In general, I listen to music, watch clips of my time on YouTube, take advantage of my grandchildren and, from time to time, watch basketball games.
And of course, I take advantage of the company of my wife, Isabel, who has always been with me.
Death of actor Larry Hagman
Larry Hagman, born on September 21, 1931, in Forth Worth, Texas, became known worldwide for the leading role of John Ross Ewing, better known as J.R., in the television series "Dallas", in which he embodied an unscrupulous, fearsome and manipulative businessman.
Larry Hagman, whose role as unscrupulous oil magnate J.R. Ewing in the television series "Dallas" became a symbol of greed in the 1980s, died.
He was 81 years old.
Hagman, who had returned this year in the role of J.R. in a new season of "Dallas", died Friday night from complications of a cancer, according to a family statement sent to The Associated Press for the Warner Bros., production house of "Dallas".
"Larry was back in her beloved home town of Dallas, playing again the ironic role he loved the most," the family said.
Larry's family and close friends were with him in Dallas on this Thanksgiving holiday.
Linda Gray, who played her wife's role in the original series and later, was with Hagman when he died in a hospital in Dallas, said her press secretary, Jeffrey Lane.
He brought joy to all those who knew him.
He was creative, generous, funny, affectionate and talented, and I'm going to miss him a lot.
"He was an exceptional person and he lived life to the full," Gray said in a statement.
The doctors had diagnosed Larry Hagman with liver cirrhosis in 1992 and he had recognized that he had been drinking a lot for many years.
In 1995, he had been diagnosed with a malignant liver tumor and had been transplanted.
Several years before "Dallas", Hagman had made himself known on television as an ordinary type in the series "Jinny of My Dreams" broadcast by NBC from 1965 to 1970.
In this one, he interpreted the role of Captain Tony Nelson, an astronaut whose life was transformed when he discovered an attractive genius, interpreted by Barbara Eden, and brought her home.
He also played in two short-lived comedies, "The Good Life" (NBC, 1971-72) and "Here We Go Again" (ABC, 1973).
Among his roles in cinema are roles well received by critics in "The Group", "Harry and Tonto" and "Primary Colors".
But it was thanks to his masterful interpretation of the deliciously detestable J.R. that Larry Hagman had his greatest success.
The CBS drama series on the Ewing clan and their relatives was broadcast from April 1978 to May 1991.
The slogan "Who Killed J.R.?", invented to maintain the suspense around an episode full of emotions in which Hagman's character is almost murdered, generated speculations around the world and millions of dollars played in bets.
Thanks to this, among other things, the series reached a record audience at that time.
When the answer was revealed in an episode of November 1980, 41 million viewers were on average in front of their screen and made "Dallas" the second most watched entertainment program in the world, after the final episode of "MASH" in 1983, which had gathered 50 million viewers.
It was J.R.'s sister-in-law, Kristin (interpreted by Mary Crosby) who shot him.
J.R. had her pregnant and then threatened to accuse her of prostitution if she did not leave the city, but others also had reason to assault her.
Hagman played the role of Ewing as a corrupt and insatiable man but with a charismatic smile: a dishonest entrepreneur and an unfaithful husband trying to get his alcoholic wife Sue Ellen (Linda Gray).
"I know what it would take as an epitaph for J.R," Hagman said in 1988.
We should write, "This is the honest citizen J.R. Ewing."
This is the only part he's lost.
Victoria Principal, co-protagonist of the original series, remembered this Friday of Hagman as a man " immense, both on the small screen and in life".
It is unforgettable, and irreplaceable, for millions of fans around the world, and in the heart of each of us, who have had the chance to know and love it.
Ten episodes of the new edition of "Dallas" were broadcast a few months ago with great success on the TNT channel.
The recording of five episodes is already finished for the second season and a sixth is being realized, the channel informed.
For the time being, neither Warner nor TNT have reported on how Hagman's death will be integrated into the series.
