A course on the "End of the World" has just begun
Every week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs and global warming.
This semester, when the professor of religion Stuart Charmé decided to give a course on the end of the world, he knew that he was launching an irresistible hook there: the end of the "great count" of the Maya calendar, on December 21, to which many people refer as proof of the end of the imminent world.
But Professor Charmé had no idea what awaited him in the following months: the catastrophic hurricane Sandy, a fiscal gulf that some have nicknamed "the Armageddon of debt" and a growing conflict involving Israel, the place where Christian theorists of the end times thought that the apocalypse would be triggered.
"I didn't realize it was going to be the most apocalyptic semester I've ever known," Professor Charmed told his students at Rutgers-Camden University, New Jersey, this week.
If we analyze what happened in the world today as if we were 30 days later and we were telling it, it was a very good time.
And it must be remembered that what is bad is good for those who believe in the apocalypse.
And he is not the only teacher to teach about "the end of the world" this semester, which will, in theory, be the last in history.
In Temple, Assistant Professor Barry Vacker gives the course "Media, Culture and End of the World".
Every week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs and global warming.
"We analyze this because these ideas proliferate over time," he said, and how they offer hypothetical scenarios guides a certain human behavior.
If nuclear weapons fell into the hands of terrorists, for example, a war could break out.
This month, students will analyze films with apocalyptic themes and study how they can be compared with examples of real life.
"I tried to inform my students about what was possible, probable, credible and impossible," Vacker said.
On the main campus of the State University of Pennsylvania, Latin American History Professor Matthew Restall and his colleague Amara Solari, an assistant professor of Art History and Anthropology, teamed up to give a course, simply entitled "The End of the World".
"We add "2012" to have the opportunity to give the course again, in case the world does not disappear," said Professor Restall.
Despite the "imminent disaster", students must study, create projects and pass their final exams.
In the state of Pennsylvania, the final exam will be passed on the eve of the Apocalypse, which leaves students with no choice but to work "until the very night of the supposed end of the world," Restall said.
The courses proved to be quite popular.
"It was complete in two hours," Restall said about his course for high-level students, made up of 35 students.
We received e-mail messages several weeks before the beginning of the semester, from people asking if there was still room.
Students, for their part, ensure that the course is one of the most interesting.
"It fascinates me to see what people are able to do to comfort themselves," says Bridgid Robinson, a 23-year-old student in religion and sociology from Haddonfield, New Jersey, Rutgers-Camden University.
For the fear of the Apocalypse, whether secular or religious, is only a matter of comfort, or lack of comfort.
Will Wekesa, a 25-year-old student in psychology and infirmary, claims to have watched all the apocalyptic films.
"I had never heard of a course that taught this subject," he said.
I appreciate it.
But none of the students interviewed, let alone a teacher, told us to believe in the end of the world date of December 21.
"Our first project dealt with the Mayan prophecy, and in a way we discredited it," says Julie zegle, a senior student in Temple, aged 21 and from West Chester.
The Maya never predicted the end of the world, it's only a key date on the calendar, Restall said.
But I concede that there is an anxiety related to the apocalypse in Western culture, dating back centuries, which causes people to react to changes in their environment by predicting the end of the world.
The Internet has sparked an upsurge in these speculations.
"In other places around the world, people don't think about it," he says.
This is mostly the English-speaking world.
Joseph Dougherty, a professor of religion at La Salle University who teaches in the Philippines this year, responded quickly when asked if he knew that there were courses here on "the end of the world".
"The Philippines does not participate in the end of the world," he replied, as if it were an exception from a higher authority.
We have a grace from the Pope.
Restall points out that over the years, we have talked about the many supposed dates of the last judgment, and he says that if nothing happens on December 21, "people will immediately start thinking about the next date" or thinking about the fact that December 21 marks the beginning of a seven-year period at the end of which the world will disappear.
Students and teachers take the date lightly.
Many told us that they were thinking of going to "end of the world" parties.
"Sometimes I call friends and we laugh together," commented Samira Ford, a 20-year-old communications student.
